### @apply Directive for Extraction

When you repeat the same utility pattern, extract it using `@apply` in a CSS file:

```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

@layer components {
  .btn-primary {
    @apply bg-blue-600 text-white font-semibold py-2 px-6 
           rounded-lg shadow-md hover:bg-blue-700 
           focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-400
           transition-all duration-200;
  }

  .card {
    @apply bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md p-6;
  }
}
```

Usage in HTML:

```html
<button class="btn-primary">Click Me</button>
<div class="card">Content</div>
```

### Creating Utility Components

Extract larger patterns while keeping flexibility:

```css
@layer components {
  .input-field {
    @apply w-full border border-gray-300 rounded-lg px-4 py-2
           focus:border-blue-500 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-200
           focus:outline-none transition-colors;
  }

  .badge {
    @apply inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full 
           text-sm font-medium;
  }

  .badge-success {
    @apply badge bg-green-100 text-green-800;
  }

  .badge-error {
    @apply badge bg-red-100 text-red-800;
  }
}
```

### Component Classes vs Utility Approach

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|----------|------|------|
| Pure utilities | Flexible, no extra CSS, smaller bundles | Verbose HTML, repetition |
| Component classes | Cleaner HTML, reusable | Extra CSS, less flexible |
| Hybrid (recommended) | Balance of both | Slightly more setup |

### Partial Extraction

Extract only the most repetitive parts, keep inline utilities for unique styles:

```css
@layer components {
  .section-heading {
    @apply text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900;
  }
}
```

```html
<h2 class="section-heading mb-4 text-center">Title</h2>
<h2 class="section-heading mb-2 text-left">Another Title</h2>
```

### Component Best Practices

- Extract only when you see the pattern **3+ times**
- Keep extracted components **focused** (single responsibility)
- Use `@layer components` for component styles
- Don't over-extract - utility classes are the primary way
- Use **Tailwind's config** for design tokens, not custom CSS
- Name components semantically (`.card`, `.btn`, `.badge`)
- Consider using a **frontend framework** (React, Vue) for true components

codeExample:
/* styles.css */
@layer components {
  .card {
    @apply bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md overflow-hidden 
           hover:shadow-lg transition-shadow duration-300;
  }

  .card-image {
    @apply w-full h-48 object-cover;
  }

  .card-body {
    @apply p-6;
  }

  .card-title {
    @apply text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2;
  }

  .card-text {
    @apply text-gray-600 leading-relaxed;
  }
}

<!-- usage.html -->
<div class="card max-w-sm">
  <img src="photo.jpg" alt="" class="card-image">
  <div class="card-body">
    <h3 class="card-title">Card Title</h3>
    <p class="card-text">This is reusable card component using @apply.</p>
    <button class="mt-4 btn-primary">Read More</button>
  </div>
</div>
